U||CHAPTER I
U||  Pirates of Space
U||   Apparently motionless to her passengers and crew, the Interplanetary
U||   liner Hyperion bored serenely onward through space at normal
U||   acceleration. In the railed-off sanctum in one corner of the control
U||   room a bell tinkled, a smothered whirr was heard, and Captain Bradley
U||   frowned as he studied the brief message upon the tape of the
U||   recorder--a message flashed to his desk from the operator's panel. He
U||   beckoned, and the second officer, whose watch it now was, read aloud:
U||   "Reports of scout patrols still negative."
U||   "Still negative." The officer scowled in thought. "They've already
U||   searched beyond the widest possible location of the wreckage, too. Two
U||   unexplained disappearances inside a month--first the Dione, then the
U||   Rhea--and not a plate nor a lifeboat recovered. Looks bad, sir. One
U||   might be an accident; two might possibly be a coincidence...." His
U||   voice died away. What might that coincidence mean?
U||   "But at three it would get to be a habit," the captain finished the
U||   thought. "And whatever happened, happened quick. Neither of them had
U||   time to say a word--their location recorders simply went dead. But of
U||   course they didn't have our detector screens nor our armament.
U||   According to the observatories we're in clear ether, but I wouldn't
U||   trust them from Tellus to Luna. You have given the new orders, of
U||   course?"
U||   "Yes, sir. Detectors full out, all three courses of defensive screen on
U||   the trips, projectors manned, suits on the hooks. Every object detected
U||   in the outer space to be investigated immediately--if vessels, they are
U||   to be warned to stay beyond extreme range. Anything entering the fourth
U||   zone is to be rayed."
U||   "Right--we are going through!"
U||   "But no known type of vessel could have made away with them without
U||   detection," the second officer argued. "I wonder if there isn't
U||   something in those wild rumors we've been hearing lately?"
U||   Now, systematically and precisely, the great Cone of Battle was coming
U||   into being; a formation developed during the Jovian Wars while the
U||   forces of the Three Planets were fighting in space.
U||   "Bah! Of course not!" snorted the captain. "Pirates in ships faster
U||   than light--fifth order rays--nullification of gravity--mass without
U||   inertia--ridiculous! Proved impossible, over and over again. No, sir,
U||   if pirates are operating in space--and it looks very much like it--they
U||   won't get far against a good big battery full of kilowatt-hours behind
U||   three courses of heavy screen, and a good solid set of multiplex rays.
U||   Properly used, they're good enough for anybody. Pirates, Neptunians,
U||   angels, or devils--in ships or on sunbeams--if they tackle the Hyperion
U||   we'll burn them out of the ether!"
U||   Leaving the captain's desk, the watch officer resumed his tour of duty.
U||   The six great lookout plates into which the alert observers peered were
U||   blank, their far-flung ultra-sensitive detector screens encountering no
U||   obstacle--the ether was empty for thousands upon thousands of
U||   kilometers. The signal lamps upon the pilot's panel were dark, its
U||   warning bells were silent. A brilliant point of white in the center of
U||   the pilot's closely ruled micrometer grating, exactly upon the
U||   cross-hairs of his directors, showed that the immense vessel was
U||   precisely upon the calculated course, as laid down by the automatic
U||   integrating course-plotters. Everything was quiet and in order.
U||   "All's well, sir," he reported briefly to Captain Bradley--but all was
U||   not well.
U||   Danger--more serious far in that it was not external--was even then,
U||   all unsuspected, gnawing at the great ship's vitals. In a locked and
U||   shielded compartment, deep down in the interior of the liner, was the
U||   great air purifier. Now a man leaned against the primary duct--the
U||   aorta through which flowed the stream of pure air supplying the entire
U||   vessel. This man, grotesque in full panoply of space armor, leaned
U||   against the duct, and as he leaned a drill bit deeper and deeper into
U||   the steel wall of the pipe. Soon it broke through, and the slight rush
U||   of air was stopped by the insertion of a tightly fitting rubber tube.
U||   The tube terminated in a heavy rubber balloon, which surrounded a frail
U||   glass bulb. The man stood tense, one hand holding before his
U||   silica-and-steel helmeted head a large pocket chronometer, the other
U||   lightly grasping the balloon. A sneering grin was upon his face as he
U||   awaited the exact second of action--the carefully pre-determined
U||   instant when his right hand, closing, would shatter the fragile flask
U||   and force its contents into the primary air stream of the Hyperion!
U||   Far above, in the main saloon, the regular evening dance was in full
U||   swing. The ship's orchestra crashed into silence, there was a patter of
U||   applause and Clio Marsden, radiant belle of the voyage, led her partner
U||   out into the promenade and up to one of the observation plates.
U||   "Oh, we can't see the earth any more!" she exclaimed. "Which way do you
U||   turn this, Mr. Costigan?"
U||   "Like this," and Conway Costigan, burly young first officer of the
U||   liner, turned the dials. "There--this plate is looking back, or down,
U||   at Tellus; this other one is looking ahead."
U||   Earth was a brilliantly shining crescent far beneath the flying vessel.
U||   Above her, ruddy Mars and silvery Jupiter blazed in splendor ineffable
U||   against a background of utterly indescribable blackness--a background
U||   thickly besprinkled with dimensionless points of dazzling brilliance
U||   which were the stars.
U||   "Oh, isn't it wonderful!" breathed the girl, awed. "Of course, I
U||   suppose that it's old stuff to you, but I--a ground-gripper, you know,
U||   and I could look at it forever, I think. That's why I want to come out
U||   here after every dance. You know, I ..."
U||   Her voice broke off suddenly, with a queer, rasping catch, as she
U||   seized his arm in a frantic clutch and as quickly went limp. He stared
U||   at her sharply, and understood instantly the message written in her
U||   eyes--eyes now enlarged, staring hard, brilliant, and full of
U||   soul-searing terror as she slumped down, helpless but for his support.
U||   In the act of exhaling as he was, lungs almost entirely empty, yet he
U||   held his breath until he had seized the microphone from his belt and
U||   had snapped the lever to "emergency."
U||   "Control room!" he gasped then, and every speaker throughout the great
U||   cruiser of the void blared out the warning as he forced his already
U||   evacuated lungs to absolute emptiness. "Vee-Two Gas! Get tight!"
U||   Writhing and twisting in his fierce struggle to keep his lungs from
U||   gulping in a draft of that noxious atmosphere, and with the unconscious
U||   form of the girl draped limply over his left arm, Costigan leaped
U||   toward the portal of the nearest lifeboat. Orchestra instruments
U||   crashed to the floor and dancing couples fell and sprawled inertly
U||   while the tortured First Officer swung the door of the lifeboat open
U||   and dashed across the tiny room to the air-valves. Throwing them wide
U||   open, he put his mouth to the orifice and let his laboring lungs gasp
U||   their eager fill of the cold blast roaring from the tanks. Then,
U||   air-hunger partially assuaged, he again held his breath, broke open the
U||   emergency locker, donned one of the space-suits always kept there, and
U||   opened its valves wide in order to flush out of his uniform any
U||   lingering trace of the lethal gas.
U||   He then leaped back to his companion. Shutting off the air, he released
U||   a stream of pure oxygen, held her face in it, and made shift to force
U||   some of it into her lungs by compressing and releasing her chest
U||   against his own body. Soon she drew a spasmodic breath, choking and
U||   coughing, and he again changed the gaseous stream to one of pure air,
U||   speaking urgently as she showed signs of returning consciousness. Now,
U||   it was Clio Marsden's life.
U||   "Stand up!" he snapped. "Hang onto this brace and keep your face in
U||   this air-stream until I get a suit around you! Got me?"
U||   She nodded weakly, and, assured that she could now hold herself at the
U||   valve, it was the work of only a minute to encase her in one of the
U||   protective coverings. Then, as she sat upon a bench, recovering her
U||   strength, he flipped on the lifeboat's visiphone projector and shot its
U||   invisible beam up into the control room, where he saw space-armored
U||   figures furiously busy at the panels.
U||   "Dirty work at the cross-roads!" he blazed to his captain, man to
U||   man--formality disregarded, as it so often was in the Triplanetary
U||   service. "There's skulduggery afoot somewhere in our primary air! Maybe
U||   that's the way they got those other two ships--pirates! Might have been
U||   a timed bomb--don't see how anybody could have stowed away down there
U||   through the inspections, and nobody but Franklin can neutralize the
U||   shield of the air-room--but I'm going to look around, anyway. Then I'll
U||   join you fellows up there."
U||   "What was it?" the shaken girl asked. "I think that I remember your
U||   saying 'Vee-Two gas.' That's forbidden! Anyway, I owe you my life,
U||   Conway, and I'll never forget it--never. Thanks--but the others--how
U||   about all the rest of us?"
U||   "It was Vee-Two, and it is forbidden," Costigan replied grimly, eyes
U||   fast upon the flashing plate, whose point of projection was now deep in
U||   the bowels of the vessel. "The penalty for using it or having it is
U||   death on sight. Gangsters and pirates use it, since they have nothing
U||   to lose, being on the death list already. As for your life, I haven't
U||   saved it yet--you may wish I'd let it ride before we get done. The
U||   others are too far gone for oxygen--couldn't have brought even you
U||   around a few seconds later, quick as I got to you. But there's a sure
U||   antidote--we all carry it in a lock-box in our armor--and we all know
U||   how to use it, because crooks all use Vee-Two and so we're always
U||   expecting it. But since the air will be pure again in half an hour
U||   we'll be able to revive the others easily enough if we can get by with
U||   whatever is going to happen next. There's the bird that did it, right
U||   in the air-room! It's the chief engineer's suit, but that isn't
U||   Franklin that's in it. Some passenger--disguised--slugged the
U||   chief--took his suit and projectors--hole in duct--p-s-s-t! All washed
U||   out! Maybe that's all he was scheduled to do to us in this performance,
U||   but he'll do nothing else in this life!"
U||   "Don't go down there!" protested the girl. "His armor is so much better
U||   than that emergency suit you are wearing, and he's got Mr. Franklin's
U||   Lewiston, besides!"
U||   "Don't be an idiot!" he snapped. "We can't have a live pirate
U||   aboard--we're going to be altogether too busy with outsiders directly.
U||   Don't worry, I'm not going to give him a break. I'm taking a Standish
U||   and I'll rub him out like a blot. Stay right here until I come back
U||   after you," he commanded, and the heavy, vacuum insulated door of the
U||   lifeboat clanged shut behind him as he leaped out into the promenade.
U||   Straight across the saloon he made his way, paying no attention to the
U||   inert forms scattered here and there. Going up to a blank wall, he
U||   manipulated an almost invisible dial set flush with its surface, swung
U||   a heavy door aside, and lifted out the Standish--a fearsome weapon.
U||   Squat, huge, and heavy, it resembled somewhat an overgrown machine
U||   rifle, but one possessing a thick, short telescope, with several opaque
U||   condensing lenses and parabolic reflectors. Laboring under the weight
U||   of the thing, he strode along corridors and clambered heavily down
U||   short stairways. Finally he came to the purifier room, and grinned
U||   savagely as he saw the greenish haze of light obscuring the door and
U||   walls--the shield was still in place; the pirate was still inside,
U||   still flooding with the terrible Vee-Two the Hyperion's primary air.
U||   He set his peculiar weapon down, unfolded its three massive legs,
U||   crouched down behind it and threw in a switch. Dull red beams of
U||   frightful intensity shot from the reflectors and sparks, almost of
U||   lightning proportions, leaped from the shielding screen under their
U||   impact. Roaring and snapping, the conflict went on for seconds; then,
U||   under the superior force of the Standish, the greenish radiance gave
U||   way. Behind it the metal of the door ran the gamut of color--red,
U||   yellow, blinding whiter--then literally exploded; molten, vaporized,
U||   burned away. Through the aperture thus made Costigan could plainly see
U||   the pirate in the space-armor of the chief engineer--an armor which was
U||   proof against rifle fire and which could reflect and neutralize for
U||   some little time even the terrific beam Costigan was employing. Nor was
U||   the pirate unarmed--a vicious flare of incandescence leaped from his
U||   Lewiston, to spend its force in spitting, crackling pyrotechnics
U||   against the ether-wall of the squat and monstrous Standish. But
U||   Costigan's infernal machine did not rely only upon vibratory
U||   destruction. At almost the first flash of the pirate's weapon the
U||   officer touched a trigger; there was a double report, ear-shattering in
U||   that narrowly confined space; and the pirate's body literally flew into
U||   mist as a half-kilogram shell tore through his armor and exploded.
U||   Costigan shut off his beam, and, with not the slightest softening of
U||   one hard lineament, stared around the air-room; making sure that no
U||   serious damage had been done to the vital machinery of the
U||   air-purifier--the very lungs of the great space-ship.
U||   Dismounting the Standish, he lugged it back up to the main saloon,
U||   replaced it in its safe and again set the combination lock. Thence to
U||   the lifeboat, where Clio cried out in relief as she saw that he was
U||   unhurt.
U||   "Oh, Conway, I've been so afraid something would happen to you!" she
U||   exclaimed, as he led her rapidly upward toward the control room. "Of
U||   course you...." she paused.
U||   "Sure," he replied, laconically. "Nothing to it. How do you feel--about
U||   back to normal?"
U||   "All right, I think, except for being scared to death and just about
U||   out of control. I don't suppose that I'll be good for anything, but
U||   whatever I can do, count me in on."
U||   "Fine--you may be needed, at that. Everybody's out, apparently, except
U||   those who, like me, had a warning and could hold their breath until
U||   they got to their suits."
U||   "But how did you know what it was? You can't see it, nor smell it, nor
U||   anything."
U||   "You inhaled a second before I did, and I saw your eyes. I've been in
U||   it before--and when you see a man get a jolt of that stuff just once,
U||   you never forget it. The engineers down below got it first, of
U||   course--it must have wiped them out. Then we got it in the saloon. Your
U||   passing out warned me, and luckily I had enough breath left to give the
U||   word. Quite a few of the fellows up above should have had time to get
U||   away--we'll see 'em all in the control room."
U||   "I suppose that was why you revived me--in payment for so kindly
U||   warning you of the gas attack?" The girl laughed; shaky, but game.
U||   "Something like that, probably," he answered, lightly. "Here we
U||   are--now we'll soon find out what's going to happen next."
U||   In the control room they saw at least a dozen armored figures; not now
U||   rushing about, but seated at their instruments, tense and ready.
U||   Fortunate it was that Costigan--veteran of space as he was, though
U||   young in years--had been down in the saloon; fortunate that he had been
U||   familiar with that horrible outlawed gas; fortunate that he had had the
U||   presence of mind enough and sheer physical stamina enough to send his
U||   warning without allowing one paralyzing trace to enter his own lungs.
U||   Captain Bradley, the men on watch, and several other officers in their
U||   quarters or in the wardrooms--space-hardened veterans all--had obeyed
U||   instantly and without question the amplifiers' gasped command to "get
U||   tight." Exhaling or inhaling, their air-passages had snapped as that
U||   dread "Vee-Two" was heard, and they had literally jumped into their
U||   armored suits of space--flushing them out with volume after volume of
U||   unquestionable air; holding their breath to the last possible second,
U||   until their straining lungs could endure no more.
U||   Costigan waved the girl to a vacant bench, cautiously changed into his
U||   own armor from the emergency suit he had been wearing, and approached
U||   the captain.
U||   "Anything in sight, sir?" he asked, saluting. "They should have started
U||   something before this."
U||   "They've started, but we can't locate them. We tried to send out a
U||   general sector alarm, but that had hardly started when they blanketed
U||   our wave. Look at that!"
U||   Following the captain's eyes, Costigan stared at the high powered set
U||   of the ship's operator. Upon the plate, instead of a moving, living,
U||   three-dimensional picture, there was a flashing glare of blinding white
U||   light; from the speaker, instead of intelligible speech, was issuing a
U||   roaring, crackling stream of noise.
U||   "It's impossible!" Bradley burst out, violently. "There's not a gram of
U||   metal inside the fourth zone--within a hundred thousand kilometers--and
U||   yet they must be close to send such a wave as that. But the Second
U||   thinks not--what do you think, Costigan?" The bluff commander,
U||   reactionary and of the old school as was his breed, was
U||   furious--baffled, raging inwardly to come to grips with the invisible
U||   and undetectable foe. Face to face with the inexplicable, however, he
U||   listened to the younger men with unusual tolerance.
U||   "It's not only possible; it's quite evident that they've got something
U||   we haven't." Costigan's voice was bitter. "But why shouldn't they have?
U||   Service ships never get anything until it's been experimented with for
U||   years, but pirates and such always get the new stuff as soon as it's
U||   discovered. The only good thing I can see is that we got part of a
U||   message away, and the scouts can trace that interference out there. But
U||   the pirates know that, too--it won't be long now," he concluded,
U||   grimly.
U||   He spoke truly. Before another word was spoken the outer screen flared
U||   white under a beam of terrific power, and simultaneously there appeared
U||   upon one of the lookout plates a vivid picture of the pirate vessel--a
U||   huge, black globe of steel, now emitting flaring offensive beams of
U||   force. Her invisibility lost, now that she had gone into action, she
U||   lay revealed in the middle of the first zone--at point-blank range.
U||   Instantly the powerful weapons of the Hyperion were brought to bear,
U||   and in the blast of full-driven beams the stranger's screens flamed
U||   incandescent. Heavy guns, under the recoil of whose fierce salvos, the
U||   frame of the giant globe trembled and shuddered, shot out their tons of
U||   high-explosive shell. But the pirate commander had known accurately the
U||   strength of the liner, and knew that her armament was impotent against
U||   the forces at his command. His screens were invulnerable, the giant
U||   shells were exploded harmlessly in mid-space, miles from their
U||   objective. And suddenly a frightened pencil of flame stabbed
U||   brilliantly from the black hulk of the enemy. Through the empty ether
U||   it tore, through the mighty defensive screens, through the tough metal
U||   of the outer and inner walls. Every ether-defence of the Hyperion
U||   vanished, and her acceleration dropped to a quarter of its normal
U||   value.
U||   "Right through the battery room!" Bradley groaned. "We're on the
U||   emergency drive now. Our rays are done for, and we can't seem to put a
U||   shell anywhere near her with our guns!"
U||   But ineffective as the guns were, they were silenced forever as a
U||   frightful beam of destruction stabbed relentlessly through the control
U||   room, whiffing out of existence the pilot, gunnery, and lookout panels
U||   and the men before them. The air rushed into space, and the suits of
U||   the three survivors bulged out into drumhead tightness as the pressure
U||   in the room decreased.
U||   Costigan pushed the captain lightly toward a wall, then seized the girl
U||   and leaped in the same direction.
U||   "Let's get out of here, quick!" he cried, the miniature radio
U||   instruments of the helmets automatically taking up the duty of
U||   transmitting speech as the sound disks refused to function. "They can't
U||   see us--our ether wall is still up and their spy-sprays can't get
U||   through it from the outside, you know. They're working from
U||   blue-prints, and they'll probably take your desk next," and even as
U||   they bounded toward the door, now become the outer seal of an airlock,
U||   the annihilating ray tore through the space which they had just quitted
U||   in their flight.
U||   Through the airlock, down through several levels of passengers'
U||   quarters they hurried, and into a lifeboat, whose one doorway commanded
U||   the full length of the third lounge--an ideal spot, either for defense
U||   or for escape outward by means of the miniature cruiser. As they
U||   entered their retreat they felt their weight begin to increase. More
U||   and more force was applied to the helpless liner, until it was moving
U||   at normal acceleration.
U||   "What do you make of that, Costigan?" asked the captain. "Tractor
U||   beams?"
U||   "Apparently. They've got something, all right. They're taking us
U||   somewhere, fast. I'll go get a couple of Standishes, and another suit
U||   of armor--we'd better dig in," and soon the small room became a
U||   veritable fortress, housing as it did, those two formidable engines of
U||   destruction. Then the first officer made another and longer trip,
U||   returning with a complete suit of triplanetary space armor, exactly
U||   like those worn by the two men, but considerably smaller.
U||   "Just as an added factor of safety, you'd better put this on,
U||   Clio--those emergency suits aren't good for much in a battle. I don't
U||   suppose that you ever fired a Standish, did you?"
U||   "No, but I can soon learn how to do it," she replied, pluckily.
U||   "Two is all that can work here at once, but you should know how to take
U||   hold in case one of us goes out. And while you're changing suits you'd
U||   better put on some stuff I've got here--Service special phones and
U||   detectors. Stick this little disk onto your chest with this bit of
U||   tape; low down, out of sight. Just under your wishbone is the best
U||   place. Take off your wrist-watch and wear this one continuously--never
U||   take it off for a second. Put on these pearls, and wear them all the
U||   time, too. Take this capsule and hide it against your skin, some place
U||   where it can't be found except by the most rigid search. Swallow it in
U||   an emergency--it goes down easily and works just as well inside as
U||   outside. It is the most important thing of all--you can get along with
U||   it alone if you lose everything else, but without that capsule the
U||   whole system's shot to pieces. With that outfit, if we should get
U||   separated, you can talk to us--we're both wearing 'em, although
U||   somewhat different forms. You don't need to talk loud--just a mutter
U||   will be enough. They're handy little outfits, almost impossible to
U||   find, and capable of a lot of things."
U||   "Thanks, Conway--I'll remember that, too," Clio replied, as she turned
U||   toward the tiny locker to follow his instructions. "But won't the
U||   scouts and patrols be catching us pretty quick? The operator sent a
U||   warning."
U||   "Afraid the ether's empty, as far as we're concerned. They could
U||   neutralize our detector screens, and the scouts' detectors are the same
U||   as ours."
U||   Captain Bradley had stood by in silent astonishment during this
U||   conversation. His eyes had bulged slightly at Costigan's "we're both
U||   wearing 'em," but he had held his peace and as the girl disappeared a
U||   look of dawning comprehension came over his face.
U||   "Oh, I see, sir," he said, respectfully--far more respectfully than he
U||   had ever before addressed a mere first officer. "Meaning that we both
U||   will be wearing them shortly, I assume. 'Service Specials'--but you
U||   didn't specify exactly what Service, did you?"
U||   "Now that you mention it, I don't believe that I did," Costigan
U||   grinned.
U||   "That explains several things about you--particularly your recognition
U||   of Vee-Two and your uncanny control and speed of reaction. But aren't
U||   you...."
U||   "No," Costigan interrupted, positively. "This situation is apt to get
U||   altogether too serious to overlook any bets. If we get away, I'll take
U||   them away from her and she'll never know that they aren't routine
U||   equipment in the Triplanetary Service. As for you, I know that you can
U||   and do keep your mouth shut. That's why I'm hanging this junk on you--I
U||   had a lot of stuff in my kit, but I flashed it all with the Standish,
U||   except what I brought in here for us three. Whether you think so or
U||   not, we're in a real jam--our chance of getting away is mightly close
U||   to zero. Now that I've gone this far, I might as well tell you that I
U||   don't believe these birds are pirates at all, in the ordinary sense of
U||   the word. And it may be possible that they're after me, but I don't
U||   think so--we've covered up too...."
U||   He broke off as the girl came back, now to all appearances a small
U||   Triplanetary officer, and the three settled down to a long and
U||   eventless wait. Hour after hour they flew through the ether, but
