U||CHAPTER IV
U||  Within the Red Veil
U||   Nevia, the home planet of the marauding space-ship, would have appeared
U||   peculiar indeed to Terrestrial senses. High in the deep red heavens a
U||   fervent blue sun poured down its flood of brilliant purplish light upon
U||   a world of water. Not a cloud was to be seen in that flaming sky, and
U||   through that dustless atmosphere the eye could see the horizon--a
U||   horizon three times as distant as the one to which we are
U||   accustomed--with a distinctness and clarity impossible in our Terra's
U||   dust-filled air. As that mighty sun dropped below the horizon the sky
U||   would fill suddenly with clouds and rain would fall violently and
U||   steadily until midnight. Then the clouds would vanish as suddenly as
U||   they had come into being, the torrential downpour would cease, and,
U||   through that huge world's wonderfully transparent, gaseous envelope,
U||   the full glory of the firmament would be revealed. Not the firmament as
U||   we know it--for that hot blue sun and Nevia, her one planet-child, were
U||   many light-years distant from Old Sol and his numerous brood--but a
U||   strange and glorious firmament containing not one constellation
U||   familiar to earthly eyes.
U||   Many bridges and more tubes extended through the air from building to
U||   building, and the watery "streets" teemed with surface craft, and with
U||   submarines.
U||   Out of the vacuum of space a fish-shaped vessel of the void--the vessel
U||   that was shortly to attack so boldly both the massed fleet of
U||   Triplanetary and Roger's planetoid--plunged into the rarefied outer
U||   atmosphere, and crimson beams of force tore shriekingly the thin air as
U||   it braked its terrific speed. A third of the circumference of Nevia's
U||   mighty globe was traversed before the velocity of the craft could be
U||   reduced sufficiently to make a landing possible. Then, approaching the
U||   twilight zone, the vessel dived vertically downward, and it became
U||   evident that Nevia was neither entirely aqueous nor devoid of
U||   intelligent life. For the blunt nose of the space-ship was pointing
U||   toward what was evidently a half-submerged city, a city whose buildings
U||   were flat-topped, hexagonal towers, exactly alike in size, shape,
U||   color, and material. These buildings were arranged as the cells of a
U||   honeycomb would be if each cell were separated from its neighbors by a
U||   relatively narrow channel of water, and all were built of the same
U||   white metal. Many bridges and more tubes extended through the air from
U||   building to building, and the watery "streets" teemed with surface
U||   craft, and with submarines.
