U||CHAPTER XI
U||  Roger Carries On
U||   For gray Roger had not perished in the floods of Nevian energy which
U||   had destroyed his planetoid. While those terrific streamers of force
U||   emanating from the crimson obscurity surrounding the amphibians'
U||   space-ship were driving into his defensive screens, Roger sat impassive
U||   and immobile at his desk. His hard gray eyes moved methodically over
U||   his instruments and recorders; and after a few minutes he smiled
U||   coldly, while an expression of relief struggled fleetingly to move his
U||   expressionless face. Even though his screens were better than anyone
U||   had supposed, why admit it?
U||   "Baxter, Hartkopf, Chatelier, Anandrusung, Penrose, Nishimura,
U||   Mirsky...." He called off a list of names. "Report to me here at once!"
U||   "The planetoid is lost," he informed his select group of scientists
U||   when they had assembled, "and we must abandon it in exactly fifteen
U||   minutes, which will be the time required for the robots to fill this
U||   first section with our most necessary machinery and instruments. Pack
U||   each of you one box of the things he most wishes to take with him, and
U||   report back here in not more than thirteen minutes. Say nothing to
U||   anyone else."
U||   They filed out calmly, and as they passed out into the hall Baxter,
U||   perhaps a trifle less case-hardened than his fellows, at least voiced a
U||   thought for those they were so brutally deserting.
U||   "I say, it seems a bit thick to dash off this way and leave the rest of
U||   them; but still, I suppose...."
U||   "You suppose correctly." Bland and heartless Nishimura filled in the
U||   pause. "A small part of the planetoid may be able to escape; which, to
U||   me at least, is pleasantly surprising news. It cannot carry all of our
U||   men and mechanisms, therefore only the most important of both are
U||   saved. What would you? For the rest it is simply what you call 'the
U||   fortune of war,' no?"
