U||   range of any possible broadcast. But Cleveland had understood instantly
U||   what had happened. He now had a little data upon which to work, and his
U||   fingers were flying over the keys of the calculator.
U||   "Back blast, maximum, seventeen seconds!" he directed, crisply. "Not
U||   exact, of course, but that'll put us close enough to find 'em with our
U||   detectors!"
U||   Then for the calculated seventeen seconds the super-ship retraced her
U||   path, at the same awful speed with which she had come so far. The blast
U||   expired and there, plainly limned upon the observation plates, was the
U||   Nevian speedster.
U||   "As a computer you're good," Rodebush applauded. "So close that we
U||   can't use the neutralizers to catch him. If we use a dyne of driving
U||   force we'll overshoot him a million kilometers before I can snap the
U||   switches out."
U||   "And yet he's so far away and going so fast that if we keep our inertia
U||   on it'll take all day at full drive to overtake him." Cleveland was
U||   frankly puzzled. "What to do? Shunt in a potentiometer?"
U||   "No, we don't need it." Rodebush turned to the transmitter. "Costigan!
U||   We are going to take hold of you with a very light tractor. Don't cut
U||   it!"
U||   "A tractor--inertialess?" Cleveland wondered.
U||   "Why not?" Rodebush launched the tractor, set at its absolute minimum
U||   of power, and threw in his master switches.
U||   While hundreds of thousands of miles separating the two vessels and the
U||   tractor beam was exerting the least effort of which it was capable, yet
U||   the super-ship leaped toward the smaller craft at a pace which covered
U||   that distance in the twinkling of an eye. So rapidly were the
U||   objectives enlarging upon the plates that the automatic focusing
U||   devices could scarcely function rapidly enough to keep them in place.
U||   Cleveland flinched involuntarily and seized his arm-rests in a
U||   spasmodic clutch as he watched this, the first inertialess
U||   space-approach; and even Rodebush, who knew better than anyone else
U||   what to expect, held his breath and swallowed hard at the unbelievable
U||   rate at which the two vessels were rushing together.
U||   And if these two, who had rebuilt the space-flyer, could hardly control
U||   themselves, what of the three in the speedster, who knew nothing
U||   whatever of the super-ship's potentialities? Clio, staring into the
U||   plate with Costigan, uttered a piercing shriek, as she sank her fingers
U||   into his shoulders. Bradley swore a mighty deep-space oath and braced
U||   himself against certain annihilation. Costigan stared for an instant,
U||   unable to believe his eyes, then his hand darted to the contacts which
U||   would cut the beam. Too late. Before his flying fingers could reach the
U||   studs the Boise was upon them; had struck them in direct central
U||   impact. Moving at the full measure of her unthinkable velocity though
U||   the super-ship was at the moment of impact, yet the most delicate
U||   recording instruments of the speedster could not detect the slightest
U||   shock as the enormous globe struck the comparatively tiny torpedo and
U||   clung to it; accommodating instantly and effortlessly her own terrific
U||   pace to that of the smaller and infinitely slower craft. Clio sobbed in
U||   relief and Costigan, one arm around her, sighed hugely.
U||   "Hey, you space-fleas!" he cried. "Glad to see you and all that, but
U||   you might as well kill a man outright as scare him to death! So that's
U||   the super-ship, huh? SOME ship!"
U||   "Hello, Conway!" "Clear ether, Conway!" The two scientists answered the
U||   hail of their fellow.
U||   "I didn't realize that an inertialess approach would be quite such a
U||   terrifying spectacle, or I would have warned you," Rodebush went on.
U||   "Yes, thanks to you, the super-ship works as she should, at last. But
U||   you had better put on your suits and transfer. You might get your
U||   things ready...."
U||   "'Things' is good!" Costigan laughed, and Clio giggled sunnily.
U||   "We've made so many transfers already that what you see us in is all we
U||   have," Bradley explained. "We'll bring ourselves, and we'll hurry; that
U||   Nevian is coming up fast."
U||   "Is there anything on this ship you fellows want?" Costigan asked.
U||   "There may be, but we haven't any locks big enough to let her inside
U||   and we haven't time to study her now. You might leave her controls in
U||   neutral, so that Lyman can calculate her position if we should want her
U||   later on."
U||   "All right." The three armor-clad figures stepped into the Boise's open
U||   lock, the tractor beam was cut off, and the speedster flashed away from
U||   the now stationary super-ship.
U||   "Better let formalities go for a while," Captain Bradley interrupted
U||   the general introduction taking place. "I was scared out of nine years'
U||   growth when I saw you coming at us, and maybe I've still got the humps;
U||   but that Nevian is coming up fast, and if you don't already know it I
U||   can tell you that he's no light cruiser."
U||   "That's so, too," Costigan concurred. "Have you fellows got enough
U||   stuff so that you think you can take him? You've got the legs on him,
U||   anyway--you can certainly run if you want to!"
U||   "Run?" Cleveland laughed. "We have a bone of our own to pick with that
U||   ship. We licked her to a standstill once, until we burned out a set of
U||   generators, and since we got them fixed we've been chasing her all over
U||   space. We were chasing her when we picked up your call. See there?
U||   She's doing the running."
U||   The Nevian was running, in truth. Her commander had seen and had
U||   recognized the great vessel which had flashed out of nowhere to the
U||   rescue of the three Terrestrials; and, having once been at grips with
U||   that vengeful super-dreadnaught, he had little stomach for another
U||   encounter. Therefore his side-thrust was now being exerted in the
U||   opposite direction; he was frankly trying to put as much distance as
U||   possible between himself and Triplanetary's formidable cruiser. In
U||   vain. A light tractor was clamped on and the Boise flashed up to close
U||   range before Rodebush threw on her inertia and Cleveland brought the
U||   two vessels relatively to rest by increasing gradually his tractor's
U||   pull. And this time the Nevian could not cut the tractor. Again that
U||   shearing plane of force bit into it and tore at it, but it neither
U||   yielded nor broke. The rebuilt generators of Number Four were designed
U||   to carry the load, and they carried it. And again Triplanetary's every
U||   mighty weapon was brought into play.
U||   The "cans" were thrown, ultra-and infra-beams were driven, the furious
U||   macro-beam gnawed hungrily at the Nevian's defenses; and one by one
U||   those defenses went down. In desperation the enemy commander threw his
U||   every generator behind a polycyclic screen; only to see Cleveland's
U||   even more powerful drill bore relentlessly through it. Punctured that
U||   last defense, the end came soon. A secondary SX7 beam was now in place
U||   on mighty Ten's inner rings, and one fierce blast blew a hole
U||   completely through the Nevian cruiser. Into that hole entered
U||   Adlington's terrific bombs and their gruesome fellows, and where they
U||   entered, life departed. All defenses vanished, and under the blasts of
U||   the Boise's projectors, now unopposed, the metal of the Nevian vessel
U||   exploded instantly into a widely spreading cloud of vapor. Sparkling
U||   vapor, with perhaps here and there a droplet or two of material which
U||   had only been liquefied.
U||   So passed the sister-ship, and Rodebush turned his plates upon the
U||   vessel of Nerado. But that highly intelligent amphibian had seen all
U||   that had occurred. He had long since given over the pursuit of the
U||   speedster, and he did not rush in to do hopeless battle beside his
U||   fellow Nevians against the Terrestrials. His analytical detectors had
U||   written down each detail of every weapon and of every screen employed;
U||   and even while prodigious streamers of red force were raving out from
U||   his vessel, braking her terrific progress and swinging her around in an
U||   immense circle back toward far Nevia, his scientists and mechanics were
U||   doubling and redoubling the power of his already Titanic installations,
U||   to match and if possible to overmatch those of Triplanetary's
U||   super-dreadnaught.
U||   "Do we kill him now or do we let him suffer a while longer?" Costigan
U||   demanded.
U||   "I don't think so, yet," replied Rodebush. "Would you, Lyman?"
U||   "Not yet," replied Cleveland, grimly, reading the thought of the other
U||   and agreeing with it. "Let him pilot us to Nevia; we might not be able
U||   to find it without a guide. While we're at it we want to so pulverize
U||   that crowd that if they never come near the Solarian system again
U||   they'll think it's twenty minutes too soon!"
U||   Thus it was that the Boise, under only a few dynes of propulsion,
U||   pursued the Nevian ship. Apparently exerting every effort, she never
U||   came quite within range of the fleeing raider; yet never was she so far
U||   behind that the Nevian space-ship was not in clear register upon her
U||   observation plates. Nor was Nerado alone in strengthening his vessel.
U||   Costigan knew well and respected highly the Nevian scientist-captain,
U||   and at his suggestion the entire time of the long and uneventful flight
U||   was spent in re-enforcing the super-ship's armament to the iron-driven
U||   limit of theoretical and mechanical possibility.
U||   Thus, when Nevia and her hot, blue sun appeared upon his plates
U||   Rodebush was ready for any emergency, and hurled his battleship upon
U||   the Nevian with every weapon aflame. But so was Nerado ready; and,
U||   unlike her sister-ship, his vessel was manned by scientists well versed
U||   in the fundamental theory of the weapons with which they fought. Beams,
U||   rods, and lances of energy flamed and flared; planes and pencils cut,
U||   slashed, and stabbed; defensive screens glowed redly or flashed
U||   suddenly into intensely brilliant, coruscating incandescence. Crimson
U||   opacity struggled sullenly against violet curtain of annihilation.
U||   Material projectiles and torpedoes were launched under full beam
U||   control; only to be exploded harmlessly in mid-space, to be rayed into
U||   nothingness, or to disappear innocuously against impenetrable
U||   polycyclic screens. Both vessels were equipped completely with
U||   iron-driven mechanisms; both were manned by scientists capable of
U||   wringing the last possible watt of power from their sources. They were
U||   approximately equal in size, and each ship now wielded the theoretical
U||   ultimate of power for her mass; therefore neither could harm the other,
U||   furiously though each was trying. And more and more nearly they were
U||   approaching the red atmosphere of the world of the amphibians. Down
U||   into that crimson blanket the two warring space-ships dropped, down
U||   toward a city which Costigan recognized as that in which Nerado made
U||   his headquarters.
U||   "Better hold off a bit," Costigan cautioned. "If I know that bird at
U||   all, he's cooking up something," and even as he spoke there shot upward
U||   from the city a multitude of flashing balls. The Nevians had mastered
U||   the secret of the explosive of the fishes of the greater deeps and were
U||   launching it in a veritable storm against the Terrestrial visitor.
U||   "Those?" asked Rodebush, calmly. The detonating balls of destruction
U||   were literally annihilating even the atmosphere beyond the polycyclic
U||   screen, but that barrier was scarcely affected.
U||   "No, that," pointing out a hemispherical dome which, redly translucent,
U||   surrounded a group of buildings towering high above their neighbors.
U||   "Neither those high towers nor those screens were there the last time I
U||   was in this town. They're stalling for time down there, that's all
U||   those fireballs are for. Good sign, too--maybe they aren't ready for us
U||   yet. If not, you'd better take 'em while the taking's good; and if they
U||   are ready for us, we'd better get out of here while we're all in one
U||   piece."
U||   And in fact Nerado had been in touch with the scientists of his city;
U||   had been instructing them in the construction of converters and
U||   generators of such weight and power that they could crush even the
U||   defenses of the super-ship. They were not, however, quite done; the
U||   entirely unsuspected possibilities of speed inherent in absolute
U||   inertialessness had not entered into Nerado's calculations.
U||   "Better drop a few cans down on that dome, fellows, before they make
U||   trouble for us," suggested Rodebush to his gunners.
U||   "We can't," came Adlington's instant reply. "We've been trying it, but
U||   that's a polycyclic screen. Can you drill it? If you can, I've got a
U||   real bomb here--that special we built--that will do the trick if you
U||   can protect it from their beams until it gets down into the water."
U||   "I'll try it," Cleveland answered, at a nod from the physicist. "I
U||   couldn't drill Nerado's polycyclics, but I couldn't use any momentum on
U||   him. Couldn't ram him--he fell back with my thrust. But that screen
U||   down there can't back off, so maybe I can work on it. Get your special
U||   ready, and hang on, everybody!"
U||   The Boise looped upward, and from an altitude of miles dove downward
U||   through a storm of force-balls, rays, and shells; a dive checked
U||   abruptly as the hollow tube of energy, which was Cleveland's drill,
U||   snarled savagely down ahead of her and struck the shielding hemisphere
U||   with a grinding, lightning-splitting shock. As it struck, backed by all
U||   the enormous momentum of the plunging space-ship and driven by the full
U||   power of her mightiest generators, it bored in, clawing and gouging
U||   viciously through the tissue of that rigid and unyielding barrier of
U||   pure energy. Then, mighty drill and plunging mass against iron-driven
U||   wall, eye-tearing and furiously spectacular warfare was waged. Well it
U||   was for Triplanetary, that day, that its super ship carried ample
U||   supply of allotropic iron; well it was that her originally Gargantuan
U||   converters and generators had been doubled and quadrupled in power on
U||   the long Nevian way! For that oven-girdled fortress was powered to
U||   withstand any conceivable assault; but the Boise's power and momentum
U||   were now inconceivable, and every watt and every dyne was solidly
U||   behind that hellishly flaming, that voraciously tearing, that
U||   irresistibly ravening cylinder of energy incredible!
U||   Through the Nevian shield that cylinder gnawed its frightful way, and
U||   down its protecting length there drove Adlington's "Special" bomb.
U||   "Special" it was indeed; so great of girth that it could barely pass
U||   through the central orifice of Ten's mighty projector, so heavily
U||   charged with sensitized atomic iron that its detonation upon any planet
U||   would not have been considered for an instant if that planet's
U||   integrity meant anything to its attackers. Down the shielding pipe of
U||   force the "Special" screamed under full propulsion, and beneath the
U||   surface of Nevia's ocean it plunged.
U||   "Cut!" yelled Adlington, and as the scintillating drill expired, the
U||   bomber snapped his detonating switch.
U||   For a moment the effect of the explosion seemed unimportant. A dull,
U||   low rumble was all that was to be heard of a concussion that jarred red
U||   Nevia to her very center; and all that could be seen was a slow heaving
U||   of the water. But that heaving did not cease. Slowly, so slowly it
U||   seemed to the observers now high in the heavens, the waters rose up and
U||   parted; revealing a vast chasm blown deep into the ocean's rocky bed.
U||   Higher and higher the lazy, mountains of water reared; effortlessly to
U||   pick up, to smash, to grind into fragments, and finally to toss aside
U||   every building, every structure, every scrap of material substance
U||   pertaining to the whole Nevian city.
U||   Flattened out, driven backward for miles the tortured waters were
U||   urged, leaving exposed bare ground and broken rock where once had been
U||   the ocean's busy floor; while tremendous blasts of incandescent gas
U||   raved upward, buffeting even the enormous masses of the two
U||   space-ships, poised by their breathless crews so high above the site of
U||   the explosion. Then the displaced millions of tons of water rushed back
U||   into that newly rived pit, seeming to seek in that mad rush to make
U||   even more complete the already total destruction of the city. The
U||   raging torrents poured into that yawning cavern, filled it, and piled
U||   mountainously above it; receding and piling up, again and again,
U||   causing tidal waves which swept a full half of Nevia's mighty, watery
U||   globe.
U||   The city forever silenced, Rodebush again directed his weapons upon
U||   Nerado's vessel, but the Nevian was no longer fighting. For the first
U||   time in that long and bitter engagement, not a Nevian beam was in
U||   operation. His screens, however, were as capable as ever, and after a
U||   few fruitless attempts to make an impression upon them, Rodebush cut
U||   off his own offensive and turned to Costigan.
U||   "What do you make of it, Conway? You know these people better than we
U||   do; what are they up to?"
U||   "I wish to talk to you," Nerado's voice came from the speaker, "and I
U||   could not do so while the beams were operating. You are, I now
U||   perceive, a much higher form of life than any of us had thought
U||   possible; a form perhaps as high in evolution as our own. It is a pity
U||   that we did not meet you when we first neared your planet, so that much
U||   life, both Tellurian and Nevian, might have been spared. But what is
U||   past cannot be recalled. As reasoning beings, however, you will see the
U||   futility of continuing a contest in which neither of us is capable of
U||   injuring the other. You may, of course, destroy more of our Nevian
U||   cities, in which case I should be compelled to go and destroy similarly
U||   upon your earth; but, to reasoning minds, such a course of procedure is
U||   sheerest folly."
U||   Rodebush cut the communicator beam.
U||   "Does he mean it?" he demanded of Costigan. "It sounds reasonable,
U||   but...."
U||   "But fishy," broke in Cleveland. "Altogether too reasonable for a...."
U||   "Yes, he means it; every word of it," interrupted Costigan in turn.
U||   "That's the way they are. Reasonable, passionless. Funny--they lack a
U||   lot of things we have, but they've got a lot of things that I wish more
U||   of us Tellurians had too. Give me the plate--I'll talk for
U||   Triplanetary," and the beam was restored.
U||   "Captain Nerado." he greeted the Nevian commander. "Having been with
U||   you and among your people, I know that you mean what you say and that
U||   you speak for your race. Similarly, I believe that I can speak for the
U||   Triplanetary Council--the government of three of the planets of our
U||   solar system--in saying that there need be no more conflict between our
U||   peoples. I also was compelled by circumstances to do certain things
U||   which I now wish could be undone; but as you have said, the past is
U||   past. Our two races have much to gain from each other by friendly
U||   exchanges of materials and of ideas, while we can expect nothing except
U||   mutual extermination, if we elect to continue this warfare. I offer you
U||   the friendship of Triplanetary. Will you release your screens and come
U||   aboard to sign a treaty?"
U||   "I will come; my screens are down." Rodebush likewise cut off his
U||   power, although somewhat apprehensively, and a Nevian lifeboat entered
U||   the main airlock of the Boise.
U||   Then, at a table in the control room of Triplanetary's first
U||   super-ship, there was written the first Inter-Systemic Treaty. Upon one
U||   side the three Nevians; amphibious, cone-headed, loop-necked,
U||   scale-bodies, four-legged things to us monstrosities: upon the other
U||   the three humans, air-breathing, rounded-headed, shortnecked,
U||   smooth-bodied, two-legged creatures equally monstrous to the fastidious
U||   Nevians. Yet each of these representatives, of two races so different,
U||   felt respect for the other race increase within him minute by minute as
U||   the conversation went on.
U||   The Nevians had destroyed Pittsburgh, but Adlington's bomb had blown an
U||   equally populous Nevian city out of existence. One Nevian vessel had
U||   wiped out an entire unit of Triplanetary's fleet; but Costigan,
U||   practically unaided, had depopulated one Nevian city and had seriously
U||   damaged another. He had also beamed down many Nevian ships. Therefore
U||   loss of life and material could be balanced. The Solarian system was
U||   rich in iron, to which the Nevians were welcome; red Nevia possessed
U||   abundant stores of substances which upon earth were extremely rare and
U||   of vital importance. Therefore commerce was to be encouraged. The
U||   Nevians had knowledges and skills unknown to earthly science, but were
U||   entirely ignorant of many things, to us commonplace. Therefore
U||   interchange of students and of books was highly desirable. And so on.
U||   Thus was signed the Triplanetario-Nevian Treaty of Eternal Peace.
U||   Nerado and his two companions were escorted ceremoniously to their
U||   vessel, and the Boise took off in an inertialess dash toward earth,
U||   bearing the good news that the Nevian menace was no more.
U||   Clio, now a hardened space-flea, immune even to the horrible nausea of
U||   inertialessness, wriggled lithely in the curve of Costigan's arm and
U||   laughed up at him.
U||   "You can talk all you want to, Conway, but I don't like them a bit.
U||   They give me the purple jitters! I suppose that they are really
U||   estimable folks; talented, cultured, and everything; but just the same
U||   I'll bet that it will be a long, long time before anybody on earth will
U||   really, truly like them!"
